===Etymology 1===
From {{inh|en|enm|marchaundise|t=commerce, trading; buying, purchasing; business transaction, bargain, deal; agreement; trade, vocation; merchandise, goods, wares; possessions, wealth; reward; ability or right to carry on business; market; communication between God and humans; sale of indulgences; simony; paid advocate or orator (?)}},<ref>{{R:MED Online|entry=marchaundīse|pos=n|id=16587756}}</ref> from {{der|en|xno|marchaundise}} and {{der|en|fro|marcheandise}} (modern {{cog|fr|marchandise}}), from {{der|en|fro|marcheant|t=seller, vendor}} (ultimately from {{der|en|la|mercātus|t=buying and selling, trade, traffic; market; marketplace}}, possibly originally {{der|en|ett|-}}) + {{m|fro|-ise|pos=suffix forming {{glossary|feminine}} nouns, often denoting a quality or state}}. The English word is analysable as {{suffix|en|merchant|ise}}.

